VFD Group Plc, a proprietary investment company, has said it will pay its shareholders N10.79 per share with a bonus of one for every two shares owned for the year 2021. The Group Managing Director/ Chief Executive officer, VFD Group, Nonso Okpala, disclosed this while presenting its financial result for the year ended December 31, 2021 during its annual general meeting in Lagos on Tuesday. He said, “Based on the results, VFD Group Plc has proposed a final dividend of N10.78 per share with an additional bonus share for every two shares held by its shareholders. “This is N2.3 per share higher than the dividend paid last year, thereby reaffirming the commitment made to its shareholders to continuously grow wealth.” The major highlights of the results presented showed that gross earnings for the Group grew by 50 per cent to N9.95bn, from N6.65bn in 2020; interest income grew by 99 per cent to N7.33bn, from N3.69bn in 2020; trading and other non-interest income grew by 156 per cent to N10.26bn, from N4.01bn in 2020. It added that the group recorded a 64 per cent growth in shareholders’ funds to N14.64bn, from N8.92bn in 2020; and total assets growth of 26 per cent to N102.82bn, from N81.68bn in 2020. Okpala said, “The 2021 was a difficult year for the Group because we were forced to navigate the most difficult health and economic times in recent history. “Regardless, VFD Group was able to weather the storm and deliver an impressive financial performance. We are confident that our diverse portfolio of investments, products, and services, as well as our people, have placed us in an excellent position to continue providing superior value to all our stakeholders.” He noted that an assessment of strategic activities in 2021 showed the significant strides made towards additional capital raise, improved efficiency, and cross-border expansion activities. Other significant accomplishments in the year included: investment in Piggyvest and Cashpot; the establishment of three investment entities – HEREL, ARTSPLIT, and Asfalizo Acquisition; substantial investment in Venture Platforms, and the acquisition of a five per cent stake in the Nigerian Exchange Group, Nigeria’s leading exchange business.  Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com